<Base
  title="About — how to talk to robots"
  description="How to Talk to Robots is an open-source, community-driven AI literacy resource built by educators and engineers to bridge the digital divide."
>
  <article class="prose section">
    <h1>About</h1>
    <p>
      <strong>How to Talk to Robots</strong> is an open-source, community-driven
      resource built by educators and engineers to bridge the digital divide.
      Everything here is free: plain-English guides, copy-paste prompts, and
      frameworks for using AI tools like ChatGPT and Claude in real life.
    </p>
    <p>
      Our angle is simple: AI should be a <em>thinking partner, not a
      shortcut</em>. By combining neuroscience with Socratic frameworks, we move
      beyond simple “hacks.” We help individuals and teams learn to use AI in a
      way that makes them sharper — better questioners, better readers, better
      decision-makers.
    </p>
    <h2>Who's behind it</h2>
    <p>
      The project was started by
      <a href="https://amandagrutza.com">Amanda Grutza</a>, creative
      technologist and founder of
      <a href="https://thirdspaced.com">Third Space</a>, and is community
      co-created with a team of passionate educators and engineers.
    </p>
    <h2>How the site is built</h2>
    <p>
      True to the mission, this site is
      <a href="https://github.com/thirdspaced/talktorobots">open source</a> —
      a fast, accessible static site with no trackers and no paywall. Every
      resource in the library is a plain text file anyone can improve.
    </p>
    <p>
      Want to help? <a href="/contribute/">Contribute a prompt or guide</a>, or
      <a href="/contact/">get in touch</a> about workshops for your school or team.
    </p>
  </article>
</Base>
